These figures come from an engineering-wide survey on AI usage and experience at Fortris.

AI entered the engineering teams without pretending to be magic.

Release notes were generated by AI from commits #link("ref2", super[[2]]), GitLab AI bots assisted merge requests #link("ref3", super[[3]]),
and failed Kubernetes syncs jobs triggered automated AI context analysis to help developers understand outside their comfort zone where the problem is #link("ref4", super[[4]]).



= Working With Humans
Reliability is leverage only if people can use it.

Preview environments #link("ref5", super[[5]]) matured into a collaboration tool for UI teams and QA teams.
Deployments became comprehensive: ci/cd job logs surfaced reasons, ArgoCD state became
visible inside pipelines, and rocketchat notifications began reducing guesswork.

Delivery started becoming less of a coordination tax.

= Direction, Not Hope
The year opened decisively: Kubernetes would be the system of record, not a parallel path.

MongoDB control moved into Kubernetes via platform-owned Helm charts #link("ref6", super[[6]]) #link("ref7", super[[7]]). Infisical became the central secret manager #link("ref8", super[[8]]), replacing scattered values files and pipeline variables. CI/CD learned how to deploy to real Kubernetes environments, including production.

Nothing here was flashy. It was alignment.

= State, Limits, and Operability
If a platform cannot handle state, it is a scheduler.

StatefulSets were added to the base application chart. MongoDB and Redis #link("ref9", super[[9]]) gained
supported Helm charts with operating guides. Resource quotas and limit ranges
became explicit defaults across namespaces. Vault backup tooling was rebuilt
with health checks, encryption signatures, and observability.

This did not make systems simpler. It made them survivable.

= Stability as a Precondition
Before production confidence, instability had to be removed.

Registry access was centralized through a platform-managed chart. Pod
Disruption budgets and rolling update strategies were aligned with availability
realities. Automatic reloads were disabled for stateful Vault and Sentinel
workloads. ArgoCD diffing was tuned to reduce false drift and explain failures.

The platform stopped surprising people. That is what trust starts with.

= Production Trust, Earned
Theory met consequence when BCoin, our main bridge with the Bitcoin blockchain, went live on Kubernetes using Helm and
GitOps-managed workflows. Legacy paths were not forcibly shut down. They simply became unnecessary.

Kubernetes moved from "some services run here" to "production belongs here."

= Irreversible Moves
Once the Kubernetes platform worked, it began to lock in the future.

Keycloak moved fully into Kubernetes. RDS integration became a supported capability for Kubernetes workloads. STS assume-role patterns replaced static AWS credentials for almost all platform tooling.

CI/CD pipelines stopped wasting time: merge request pipelines canceled outdated runs, ArgoCD sync jobs failed fast, and preview environments gained lifecycle rules instead of leaking namespaces.

This was not innovation. It was discipline.

= Scale Without Waste
As confidence grew, some waste became visible.

Artifact retention policies reduced GitLab and Nexus footprints. GitLab Runners were isolated and right-sized. Spot capacity was introduced carefully in dev. Cost attribution aimed at becoming explicit through Kubernetes metadata tied to teams and products.

The platform became lighter as it grew.

= Automation as a Delivery System
Automation stopped being a side project and became part of the delivery path.

Genaro David stepped up to lead QA execution, and Software Engineers in Test (SETs) moved into an enabler pod with domain ownership and a single Jira backlog. E2E suites and performance tests were stabilized through a dedicated SET firefight loop that detects and fixes instability early. Quality gates became more explicit, so release decisions started to rely on signal instead of guesswork.

The outcome was fewer ignored failures, clearer signals, and automation teams that can be trusted when delivery is moving fast.

